<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Britain's Olympic hopes end as Sydney tops vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTE CARLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SYDNEY is to host the Olympics in the year 2000, the International Olympic
Committee decided last night.
The vote dashed the hopes of Beijing to gain much-sought international
recognition and of Manchester to bring the Games to Britain for the first
time since 1948.
Beijing had been favourite to win. The Chinese government had made the
Olympics an intense foreign policy objective since 1990. Manchester was
eliminated in the third round of voting but was always far behind Beijing
and Sydney even though it led Berlin and Istanbul, the other two candidates.
China's candidature was favoured by the IOC's higher echelons as a symbol of
the Olympic movement's power to effect benevolent change in the world.
Voting members, however, were troubled by China's human rights record.
In the ballot among 88 IOC members in Monte Carlo, the Australian city beat
Beijing by two votes, 45-43, after four rounds of voting. It followed a day
of presentations by the five cities and three years of campaigning.
Beijing led through every round of voting until the last. Istanbul was the
first of the five cities to be eliminated, followed by Berlin. With
Manchester still in a three-way hunt, Beijing was within five votes of
outright victory. But when the British contender was eliminated, the bulk of
its support shifted to Australia; eight votes to Sydney and only three to
China.
Exuberant Australian representatives attending the announcement danced
around the conference hall, drowning out the rest of the speech by Mr Juan
Antonio Samaranch, IOC president. Some of the Manchester delegation broke
down in tears and hugged each other in consolation.
Sydney's victory may boost the drive for ending constitutional ties with
Britain being led by Mr Paul Keating, prime minister.
In an emotional television interview, Mr Keating alluded to this last night
when he said the Games 'will coincide with the centenary of our federation
and will show the world Australia as a nation in its own right'.
'Things can be so much better for Australia than many Australians believe.
Some very hard-nosed internationalists have just given the affirmative on
that.'
In Sydney, the result was celebrated by tens of thousands at Circular Quay,
which cradles the Opera House. Shares opened buoyantly with the market 26
points up in early trading.
A throng estimated at 15,000 in Manchester city centre did not allow the
loss to dampen their spirits, breaking into a mass rendition of 'Always look
on the bright side of life.'
All-night party ends in cheers for Sydney, Page 8
Defeated Manchester counts its blessings, Page 11
</TEXT>
