<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DERIVATIVES traders appeared satisfied yesterday with a session which saw
stock index futures moving erratically before closing with the December
contract on the FT-SE 100 Index near to the fair value premium, writes Terry
Byland.
Trading volume eased as, in the early part of the session at least, tensions
over the political drama in Russia relaxed somewhat.
The session was punctuated by rumours, sometimes reported on the
international newswires, of developments or impending developments in
Moscow. Early trading saw the December contract move up to 3,041 before
reversing to 3,015.
Switching into UK gilts from other European markets inspired a closing rally
in equities and December closed at 3,025, a premium of 22 against cash,
compared with 24 on the fair value premium which allows for dividend flows
and the cost of carrying the underlying stocks until December. Volume
dropped from 15,230 to 10,303 lots.
Business in traded options fell sharply, from 42,110 on Wednesday to 28,690
yesterday, with the FT-SE 100 option recording 8,600 contracts against
14,753. The Euro FT-SE option traded 5,477 contracts, while pressures from
the equity market brought 1,475 deals in Guinness. J. Sainsbury saw 1,220
lots transacted as food retailer shares fell sharply, and Tarmac (1,062) was
also active.
</TEXT>
