<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / International Company News: Pirelli still in red at halftime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PIRELLI, the Italian tyres and cables group, remained firmly in the red in
the first six months of this year, in spite of continuing efforts to lower
its break-even point by cutting costs.
Net losses amounted to L62.7bn (Dollars 40m) against net earnings of L77bn
last year. However, comparisons are clouded by extraordinary factors.
Although Pirelli said it had only remained in profit for the first six
months of 1992 because of extraordinary items and asset sales, this year's
result was also boosted by a L72bn extraordinary gain.
The gain represents part of the proceeds from the sale of Pirelli's shares
and options in Continental, the bigger German rival it tried to take over in
1990-91.
At the operating level, Pirelli claimed that this year's first-half net
losses of L23bn were in line with last year's figure.
Sales rose by 9 per cent to L4,640bn, largely because of the lower value of
the lira, which inflated foreign earnings in lira terms.
Group indebtedness remained little changed, while interest charges fell
slightly and should continue to decline in the second half, the company
said.
Pirelli warned that the outlook for the rest of the year remains gloomy,
meaning that trading in the second half is unlikely to show any improvement
on the trend reported in the January-June period.
Net results would continue to be affected by extraordinary factors, the
company said, in particular, continuing heavy restructuring costs and
write-downs.
</TEXT>
