FT  24 SEP 93 / International Company News: Travelers agrees to offer by
Primerica
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARD of Travelers, one of the biggest US composite insurance companies,
agreed yesterday to an offer from financial services group Primerica for the
73 per cent of the company it does not already own.
The Dollars 4.1bn deal had already been by approved by the board of
Primerica, but must still win the support of shareholders of both companies
and insurance regulators in a number of states.
The Travelers takeover would mark the culmination of a drive by Mr Sanford
Weill, chairman and chief executive of Primerica, to turn his consumer
finance, stockbroking and insurance group into one of the biggest
diversified financial services groups in the US.
Based on yesterday's market valuations of the two companies, the takeover
would create a group with a market capitalisation of about Dollars 17bn -
identical to American Express, the financial services group which Mr Weill
left in the mid-1980s to begin building his own operation.
Mr Weill said the deal would give Primerica 'an even more diversified
earnings stream, a large portion of which is recurring and predictable'.
