<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / International Company News: Charge hits shares at US brewery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Anheuser-Busch, the US brewery and food group, slid in New York
yesterday morning after the company announced that it would post a loss in
the third quarter as a result of a one-time pre-tax charge of Dollars 565m.
The company said the provision, which works through at about Dollars 1.26 a
share, would cover the cost of implementing a package of 'significant
organisational and operational changes'. In the third quarter of 1992,
Anheuser-Busch posted net income of Dollars 318m, or Dollars 1.12.
The announcement, which had come after the close of the New York Stock
Exchange on Wednesday, triggered a sharp reaction when the market opened
yesterday, with the share price falling Dollars 2 to Dollars 43 5/8 in early
trading.
In the most prominent feature of the plan, the company will reduce salaried
staff by 10 per cent, or about 1,200 workers, by the end of next year.
It said it hoped to achieve the cuts primarily through attrition and an
early retirement package to be offered to employees aged 53 or older.
