<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Wembley doubles to Pounds 2.89m - Profit
from disposal of investments behind advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WEMBLEY, owner of the north London stadium complex and greyhound tracks,
more than doubled first-half profits to Pounds 2.89m, but only after the
sale of investments.
Profits from continuing operations fell from Pounds 8.02m to Pounds 6.11m
with the main stadium and the smaller Arena both hosting fewer events and US
greyhound operating profits falling 63 per cent.
Group pre-tax profits, including the Pounds 5.6m surplus from the sale of
shares in the Ticketing Group and Autotote, rose from Pounds 1.07m to Pounds
2.89m after an interest bill of Pounds 6.9m (Pounds 7.9m). Sales were
marginally higher at Pounds 78m.
Earnings per share were 0.58p compared with losses of 0.43p, but the interim
dividend is passed.
The group made disposals of Pounds 15m in the first half and Sir Brian
Wolfson, chairman, said he expected at least the same in the second half.
But net debt fell by only Pounds 5m to Pounds 139m, leaving gearing at 78
per cent. Wembley reiterated that in line with an agreement with its banks
last year it will cut Pounds 40m from its borrowings by March 31 1994 and
Pounds 50m by the end of that year.
The Wembley complex made an operating profit of Pounds 4.4m, down from
Pounds 4.49m in the same period last year. Sir Brian said the performance
was commendable given that there were no main stadium pop concerts in the
first half, compared with seven in the same period last year, and that the
number of events in the Arena fell by 13 to 53.
Profits from UK greyhound operations, which are for sale, fell 11 per cent
to Pounds 1.24m, hit by evening opening of betting shops.
In the US, the greyhound operating profit fell from Pounds 1.55m to Pounds
580,000 because the Lincoln, Rhode Island, track met stiff competition from
a casino based in Connecticut.
Sir Brian said Lincoln was fighting back and that the Colorado operations
had not been affected.
COMMENT
The boardroom coup against Sir Brian Wolfson may not have materialised. But
the chronically optimistic Wembley chairman is not off the rocks. Asset
sales have trimmed only Pounds 5m from the debt mountain; operating profits
remain uncomfortably dependent on world music stars choosing to tour,
something the recession has persuaded many not to do; and profits at the US
greyhound operation have collapsed just as it was being groomed for sale.
Shareholders can therefore expect more rough water before their shares find
any buoyancy. Nor can they rely on someone providing the finance to back a
hostile bid by disaffected former directors. Though Sir Brian plotted the
course and was at the helm when the group went aground, he can probably
count on support of shareholders representing 25 per cent of the company.
</TEXT>
