<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / La Generale may use cash from cement sale for acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HEIDELBERGER Zement, Germany's largest producer of building materials, has
bought a 43 per cent stake in CBR, the Belgian cement company, triggering a
BFr53bn (Pounds 1bn) offer for the whole company.
If the deal is approved by competition authorities, the merged group will be
the fourth largest building materials company in Europe, with annual
turnover of DM5.23bn (Pounds 2bn).
Heidelberger agreed to buy the stake from Societe Generale de Belgique,
Belgium's largest holding company, which has been trying to reduce its
exposure to cyclical industrial stocks.
Viscount Etienne Davignon, chairman of La Generale, said the cash raised by
the sale of the CBR stake would be held in reserve for possible
acquisitions. 'It's clearly not a cushion (against recession) and we don't
intend to put it into bits and pieces,' he said. Mr Davignon added that
without the additional money, La Generale had been unable to fulfil its
ambition to be an active 'professional investor' in its businesses.
The German group said that it was seeking a majority stake in CBR, but it
wanted to maintain its stock market listing, and allow it to develop as 'an
independently managed Belgian-Dutch company with a large independent
shareholder base'.
The German company is paying BFr22.5bn for La Generale's shares, at
BFr11,750 each. That compares with the price of BFr11,475 at which CBR's
shares were suspended on the Brussels bourse two days ago. The shares
remained frozen yesterday. La Generale's shares fell BFr100 to close at
BFr2,490 and in Frankfurt Heidelberger was suspended at DM1,090. Under
Brussels stock exchange rules, Heidelberger must offer at least BFr11,750 to
other shareholders.
Mr Peter Schuhmacher, Heidelberger chairman, said both companies were
efficient and modern and recent investments would bear fruit immediately.
Heidelberger produces a wider range of building materials than CBR, which
concentrates on cement, aggregates and concrete.
La Generale sees the financial and services sectors as its main source of
profit. The CBR stake accounted for about 9.6 per cent of the value of the
Belgian group's portfolio at end-June.
Results and background, Page 26
</TEXT>
