<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Guinness suffers 9% decline: Reduced sales of deluxe Scotch
whisky varieties erode margins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GUINNESS, the UK brewing and spirits group, reported a 9 per cent decline in
first-half profits yesterday, and forecast flat full-year profits and only
modest growth in 1994.
Mr Anthony Greener, chairman and chief executive, said world conditions this
year were 'proving to be less favourable than anticipated. We are still
seeing signs of further deterioration in some major markets.'
He insisted that the group was performing resiliently with key brands
maintaining, or gaining, share in most important regions.
But Guinness shares fell 32p to close at 427p.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to June 30 of Pounds 320m were at the
lower end of market expectations. The group announced that the full-year
results would be hit by a renewed contribution of Pounds 30m to its pension
fund.
Operating profits fell 7 per cent to Pounds 384m on turnover 13 per cent
ahead at Pounds 1.98bn. Profits from United Distillers, the spirits
division, dipped 8 per cent to Pounds 280m on turnover of Pounds 1.11bn
(Pounds 981m).
Though Scotch whisky volumes rose 2 per cent, sales of deluxe brands were
lower. The change in the sales mix, competitive pricing and increased
marketing costs cut operating margins from 31 to 25 per cent.
Most European markets were depressed. Volume sales were well down in Germany
and Spain, but increased substantially in Greece. In the UK there were signs
of a slowdown in the rate of decline, but prices remained under pressure.
Conditions in Japan and Thailand were difficult. Sales improved in the US,
but volumes declined in Brazil and Mexico.
Brewing contributed Pounds 104m profits, down 4 per cent, on turnover 12 per
cent ahead at Pounds 867m. Cruzcampo, the Spanish operation, contributed
only Pounds 9m compared with Pounds 22m last time.
In Britain, stout volumes were only slightly lower but a continuing decline
in the market, 2 per cent down in the first half, and price competition was
'likely to make profit growth difficult to achieve', Mr Greener said.
He added that there was considerable untapped potential in the Guinness
stout brand - and the group was focusing on expansion in the Caribbean
market with an offer of between Pounds 41m and Pounds 45m for a 51-55 per
cent stake in Desnoes &amp; Geddes, the Jamaican brewer of Red Stripe lager.
Diluted earnings per share were 8 per cent lower at 11.6p. The interim
dividend goes up from 3.35p to 3.62p.
Lex, Page 20; Pensions, Jamaican deal, Page 23
</TEXT>
