<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: Wm Morrison
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Chill winds from the north blew through the food retailing sector yesterday
and knocked another 5 per cent from Tesco and Sainsbury's share prices.
William Morrison's interim figures showed just how pressure on margins is
increasing with turnover up by almost 20 per cent and profits up by barely
5. Equally alarming was the company's acknowledgement that consumers are
trading down, and that Morrison will respond with lower margins. The message
for those superstore operators who have paid up to twice what Morrison has
forked out on a typical site is clear. Returns on capital employed - which
the grocers have long argued are not excessive - seem about to turn
distinctly sour. Aggressive pricing of branded products may also intensify
as manufacturers respond to weak sales with price cuts, exacerbating the
deflation of superstores' turnover and profits.
As share prices fall, however, the search for value starts. Morrison is
particularly badly placed since its miserly 1 per cent yield offers little
defence. Even with most of the profits retained in the business, there will
be a cash outflow over the next year to pay for the 'unabated' store opening
programme and new distribution facilities. On that basis, Tesco's 20 per
cent yield premium to the market ought to offer some comfort. Yet its higher
cost base and the suspicion that the fall in gross margins has only just
begun will weight heavy. Even mighty Sainsbury's sub-market yield looks
under threat. Sainsbury has always looked immune to the sector's troubles.
But until yesterday, that was true of Morrison, too.
</TEXT>
