<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / The Lex Column: No cheer at Guinness
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Since whisky drinkers tend to be older people, it starts to look as though
they will all be dead before they get round to trading up again. Yesterday's
interim figures from Guinness were another case of hope deferred, this time
till 1995. First half spirits profits fell 10 per cent at constant exchange
rates, and, while whisky sales rose 2 per cent by volume, luxury brands
showed a fall of 5 per cent. The longer Guinness continues to produce such
disappointing results, the more insistent is the question of whether a
strategy based on pushing customers towards ever more expensive brands is
fundamentally flawed. It is not much consolation that all the volume fall in
luxury brands was due to specific problems in Thailand, Mexico and Brazil.
These are just the sort of emerging markets tailor-made for trading up.
Having set so much store by brand enhancement, though, Guinness cannot
afford to admit to doubt. It may be right that economic recovery will
eventually revive demand for high-priced spirits, but the faint flicker of a
revival in the US is hardly yet conclusive evidence. One problem is that
high stocks will keep the base price for standard whiskies depressed. That
will limit Guinness' ability to raise prices on its premium products.
At best, it will be years before the Guinness promise feeds through to
profits growth. At worst, the company faces the tricky task of shifting from
high margin exclusive brands to a more volume-driven approach. Guinness
already seems to be hedging its bets by stepping up its marketing effort on
neglected cheaper brands. Its strong cash flow and dividend cover provide
some reassurance, but, even at last night's close of 427p, a yield of 3.5
per cent is hardly attractive.
</TEXT>
