FT  24 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Are gardens created by women so very different or more distinctive to those
created by men that BBC2 is justified in making a series called An
Englishwoman's Garden? We can find out at 8.30 when the series begins with a
look at four gardens - or can we? Sybil Spencer's garden was originally
created by her son and husband and Frieda Brown's garden in Leeds is also
the responsibility of Joe Brown. This is an intriguing start for the series.
ITV begins another of those series which seek big ratings and a socially
useful purpose - 'Crimewatch' is an obvious example. Missing (9.00) kicks
off with the somewhat startling fact that 250,000 people in Britain
disappear each year. In trying to track down missing persons the programme
will, like 'Crimewatch', use 'dramatic reconstruction'.
It is difficult to guess whether fans of opera or of animation will want to
watch BBC2's new series Animated Arias. The series will provide 12
five-minute films, shown in pairs. Today, two familiar lollipops: 'Vesti la
giubba' from 'Pagliacci' and 'La donna e mobile' from Rigoletto (9.50).
</TEXT>
