<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Delegates lectured on the
facts of political life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE serious and sober mood of the conference this week has been summed up by
the background to the platform: black and grey far outweigh the small
splashes of traditional Liberal Democrat yellow.
A sense of discipline has been imposed from the top. Instead of basking in
the by-election successes of Newbury and Christchurch, and good results in
the county council elections, Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, lectured
representatives yesterday about not missing their opportunity.
The appeal to make the most of the chance to turn 'hope into trust . . .
support into confidence . . . protest into power' seems to have two targets.
The first, and most obvious, is the kind of local campaigning tactics which
bring the national party into disrepute. While the accusations of racist
tactics in Tower Hamlets did not derail the conference, the consequent
insistence by speakers throughout the week that racism would not be
tolerated served as a continuing reminder of the level of embarrassment over
the issue.
The second target is national policy-making. While in some ways the
conference has seen a clear shift to the left compared with previous years -
for example over a commitment to full employment, increased caution about
market mechanisms and a hardening of opposition to rail privatisation - the
party has also recognised a need to produce less hostages to fortune.
But the most vivid example was yesterday's vote on pensions. By voting down
a move to uprate pensions in line with earnings, the party passed what the
leadership saw as a political maturity test.
Mr Ashdown went out of his way to congratulate delegates, albeit in the
somewhat double-edged terms of having made a 'courageous' decision.
But there is something eerie in seeing a party whose best prospect at the
next general election is to win up to 40 seats of the 650 at Westminster,
behaving as though its entire spending programme was about to be costed by
Tory Central Office for a campaign starting next week, and to be put into
practice the day after that.
It may be a reflection of Mr Ashdown's view that the present parliament will
not last until the end of its natural life in 1996 or 1997.
There are snares ahead even in the coming months. If the party does not do
well in the London local elections in May, if it suffers from its
pro-Europeanism in the Euro elections next June, or if the next
parliamentary by-elections happen to be in seats where Labour would be the
obvious beneficiary of an anti-government protest vote, then the bright
lights of the political big time may recede and the pleasures of
responsibility fade.
In the language of growing up that has been a key theme this week: the
Liberal Democrats are old enough to drive, but you might still want to wait
a while before lending them your car.
</TEXT>
