<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Party rejects call to link
pensions with earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE LEADERSHIP'S policy on pensions was carried yesterday
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
with delegates responding to appeals for realism by rejecting a call for the
restoration of the link between earnings and the level of pensions.
An amendment by Mr Archy Kirkwood, the party's chief whip and spokesman on
social security, advocated the restoration of the link removed by the
Thatcher government.
Mr Kirkwood contended that in the present stage of the political cycle it
would be premature for the party to abandon its commitment to improving the
living standard of all pensioners. 'I do not want to release the earnings
linkage until I am absolutely convinced it is unaffordable,' he said. He
estimated that the initial net cost of the move would be Pounds 250m a year.
Mr Mike Bell, a member of the party's federal policy committee, insisted:
'We sniff the scent of real power and realise that these policies may have
to be implemented.'
He suggested that the real cost of restoring the link between pensions and
earnings would be Pounds 3bn a year. Mr Bell said it would 'rip the heart
out' of the recently published consultative document in which the party
outlined costed proposals for providing dignity in old age for all
pensioners.
Sir William Goodhart, chairman of the tax and benefits working group, agreed
that a forthcoming policy paper should include a commitment to establish a
separate 'pensioners index' which more accurately reflected their living
costs than the retail price index.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, seized on the fact that the
debate had shown Mr Kirkwood to be at odds with Earl Russell, Liberal
Democrat spokesman on social security in the House of Lords. The minister
said this had demonstrated the 'anarchic confusion' in Liberal Democrat
ranks.
</TEXT>
