<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Export orders in manufacturing drop back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORRIES about the strength of the UK recovery have increased after a survey
by the Confederation of British Industry showed that export orders for
manufactured goods have slipped this month to their lowest level since
April.
The survey, published today, showed a contraction in overall order books
between August and September, although companies' optimism about their
ability to increase output rose for the ninth month in succession.
The CBI's soundings underline concerns that weak domestic demand and the
poor economic climate in key export markets may inhibit the gradual UK
upturn apparent in the past six months.
Inflationary pressures remain weak, according to the survey, with only 10
per cent of companies expecting to increase prices in the next few months.
The poll was conducted between August 27 and September 15. It covered 1,468
companies, accounting for about half of total manufacturing employment.
Sir David Lees, chairman of the CBI's economics committee, said export order
books were 'substantially' below the levels of the early summer and the
recession in the rest of Europe was 'a major cause for concern'.
The fears about future levels of exports are particularly relevant to
recovery prospects because in the past year strong export growth has been
among the main influences pushing up overall UK output.
Mr Andrew Sentance, CBI economics director, said a cut in interest rates,
now 6 per cent, might be needed over the next few months to help boost UK
demand. In a speech in Manchester he said that the poor climate for exports
meant growth would remain 'hesitant' until next year's expected recovery in
demand in continental Europe.
Sixteen per cent of companies in the survey said export order books were
above normal, with 37 per cent saying they were below normal.
This gave a negative balance of 21 percentage points for this question,
compared with one of 15 points. In September last year the negative balance
was 33 points.
As for overall levels of orders, these were thought to be above normal by 17
per cent of companies with 38 per cent thinking they were below normal. The
negative balance for this question of 21 points was slightly below the
August level of 18 points, but a marked improvement on the negative balance
of 53 points 12 months ago.
Thirty per cent of companies said they thought they would increase output
over the next four months, and 13 per cent predicted this would go down. The
resulting positive balance of 17 points is the strongest since May and
compares with a negative balance for this question of 14 points last
September.
</TEXT>
