<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / MTV set for three extra channels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MTV EUROPE, the London-based pop music satellite television channel, is
planning a move to digital technology by the beginning of next year.
This means that MTV, which already reaches more than 55m homes and as many
as 120m viewers, will be able to broadcast four channels in place of the
present one.
Mr Bill Roedy, chief executive of MTV Europe, has not yet decided how the
extra capacity will be used. The main possibilities include an additional
MTV channel tailored to the European market or a music channel aimed at an
older audience than that of MTV.
MTV is already on four satellites across Europe. The digital service is
initially expected to be aimed at European cable television networks via the
Eutelsat satellite.
Digital technology converts the television signal to digital form and
compresses it by storing the constant factors of a picture frame, only
transmitting elements that change from one frame to the next.
As many as 10 channels can be squeezed in the space of one.
MTV is also planning to join the British Sky Broadcasting subscription
package of channels next year. Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a
significant stake in BSkyB.
</TEXT>
