FT  24 SEP 93 / Treasury signals further sell-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS 'significantly more scope' for privatisation or contracting out of
central government functions than had previously been envisaged, a Treasury
minister said yesterday.
In remarks which will raise expectations that there may be more government
sell-offs, Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, said the
privatisation programme had been 'one of the clear successes of the last 14
years'.
Mr Dorrell, who was speaking to the Chartered Institute of Public Finance
and Accountancy, said that departments must ask whether the in-house
provision of a service 'enhances or detracts from' core functions.
'When once government asked 'what shall we sell?' We now ask 'what must we
keep?'' he said.
Reporting on discussions he had held on future plans with departmental
ministers, Mr Dorrell said five questions had been asked about departmental
activities: can it be abolished?; can it be privatised?; can it be
contracted out?; can it be market-tested?; and can it be given agency
status?
</TEXT>
