FT  24 SEP 93 / Council workers accept 1.5% rise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of 900,000 council manual workers last night agreed a 1.5 per cent
pay deal in line with the government's ceiling this year on wage rises for
the public sector.
Union negotiators claimed a breakthrough with an agreement to pay give
part-time workers bank holiday pay from next July.
Most white-collar town hall workers - who have still to agree this year's
claim - are expected not to vote for industrial action against the pay
ceiling. The ballot of 500,000 local staff belonging to Unison, the public
services union, will close today. The results will be be made public on
Monday.
Meanwhile Fire Brigade Union leaders will meet local authority employers
today in what they describe as a 'last chance' to secure a wage rise in
November based on the 15-year-old pay formula.
Earnings drift in the public services contributed to a rise of 7.5 per cent
in the public-sector pay bill to Pounds 92bn in 1992, according to the
Public Finance Foundation.
