<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Iraq moves on missiles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   UNITED NATIONS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ agreed yesterday to activate UN surveillance cameras at two missiles
sites, thereby clearing the way for a resumption of talks that could lead to
the lifting of an oil embargo, agencies report from the United Nations.
Iraq's ambassador, Mr Nizar Hamdoon, said Iraq had told the UN Special
Commission, in charge of dismantling Baghdad's dangerous weapons, that the
cameras could be activated at any time. He said his government had 'agreed
to activate the cameras as a sign of good will' and they could be turned on
any time the special commission wanted.
Mr Rolf Ekeus, commission chairman, had linked the activation of the cameras
to continuing arms talks with Iraq.
