<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / All-night party ends in cheers for Sydney The raucous
welcome for the 2000 Olympics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OLYMPIC 2000 bid decision may have arrived at an uncomfortable 4.30am in
Sydney. But Australia's biggest city was never going to miss its chance to
party.
At Circular Quay on the city's central harbour, tens of thousands of people
gathered to watch the event relayed live from Monte Carlo on giant
television screens. For the most part, the crowd was young, beer-swilling,
and intent on a good time. 'Syd-ney, Syd-ney', it yelled obligingly, as
presenters urged chanting. The atmosphere lay somewhere between that of a
pop concert and a football game.
But when Sydney's victory was announced, the decibel count rose to deafening
levels, and the normally decorous city centre was transformed into a
swaying, horn-blaring fiesta. Celebrating Sydney-siders hugged each other at
random. Sky and harbour twinkled with the lights from helicopters and the
flotilla of boats. Fireworks erupted over the famous harbour-side Opera
House, its 'sails' decked out in the Olympic bid colours.
In many of the city's big hotels, where residents and celebrities were
enjoying special 'all-night' packages, the partying was only marginally more
restrained. Most hotel managers had laid on continuous bar facilities, and
some had staged special events. The prize for innovation could have gone to
the Inter-continental. The upmarket hotel devised a five-course dinner, with
each segment tuned to one of contending cities - Turkish delight, Beijing
duck, a German fish-based starter accompanied by schnapps, and a
Sydney-style dessert concoction decked out in Olympic colours.
Manchester proved more of a challenge. In a leap of gastronomic imagination,
the chefs finally settled on barley soup and lamb sausage . . . served under
an umbrella.
The celebrations will now continue throughout today and well into the
weekend. This morning, the action switches from Circular Quay to
neighbouring Darling Harbour, where there will be more fireworks, bands,
concerts, and a variety of street theatre events. Pubs across the city are
expected open round the clock.
Ahead of the decision, many organisers had admitted that the task of
balancing their desire to cash in on a win, with the threat of small
turnouts if Sydney lost, was little short of a nightmare. The celebration
was called merely 'Thank You, Sydney' and one West Sydney pub hedged its
bets: its Friday programme was called 'Cheers and Tears'. In the event, they
need not have worried.
Meanwhile, Sydney's win was expected to give share prices a lift when
trading opened this morning. A cost-benefit study, undertaken by KPMG Peat
Marwick for the city's bid presenters has suggested that the nation could
enjoy a ADollars 7.3bn boost to gross domestic product over the next 11
years as a result of hosting the Games. Additional tax revenues, resulting
from extra tourists and expenditure, could amount to almost ADollars 2bn.
Local property and construction companies have been tipped to do
particularly well as a flood of building work gets under way.
For small traders, hawking Sydney souvenirs, the Games decision has been
every bit as nerve-racking. 'If Sydney loses, I'm going home to cry and get
some sleep,' said one T-shirt seller on Circular Quay yesterday afternoon.
Beside her was a pile of unsold sweatshirts. In the event, she may lack
sleep, but the dollars will certainly roll in.
The celebratory atmosphere, however, does mask some mixed views among the
city's residents about the desirability of hosting the Olympics. Most have
been enthusiastic - 'It could be as good as the America's Cup', said one
resident, ahead of last night's decision - and a recent poll suggested that
82 per cent of people in New South Wales favoured hosting the games.
But a minority of Sydney-siders have worried that estimates of a small
operating profit from the Games may prove over-optimistic, pointing to
financial problems which have developed in other Olympic cities. 'No thanx'
read the graffiti scrawled over one 'Thank You, Sydney' poster in the city
centre. The wails of the Cassandras, however, were inaudible amid the
'Syd-ney, Syd-ney' chants last night.
</TEXT>
