<TEXT>
The US health insurance industry, which would bear the brunt of price
controls under the healthcare plan, took a conciliatory approach yesterday,
applauding the aim of reducing costs and extending coverage, Richard Waters
writes from New York.
However, leading companies continued to oppose the ceiling on insurance
premiums proposed in earlier drafts.
Met Life, one of the big five insurers, said his plan 'contains extensive
price controls, payroll-based financing and regulatory health alliances
which would make managed competition unworkable.'
