<HEADLINE>
FT  24 SEP 93 / Poll pledge by Yeltsin as deputies defy decree: Government
says parliament action could 'trigger war'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON, JOHN LLOYD and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin announced yesterday he was likely to stand for
re-election in an early presidential poll next June, as Russian
parliamentary deputies met in special session to defy his decree casting
them aside.
Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the legislature's speaker, opened the meeting of the
Congress of People's Deputies despite Mr Yeltsin's decree on Tuesday
dissolving parliament ahead of elections for a new-style body in December.
The deputies ignored a government warning that the mutinous gathering could
'trigger war'.
Fuelling tension in Moscow, Russian news agencies reported a policeman had
been killed and another wounded by unidentified gunmen in a foiled attempt
last night to break into the military headquarters of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, the successor to the former Soviet Union.
One agency said the gunmen were hard-line army officers who support Russia's
conservative parliament in its struggle with Mr Yeltsin and the reformers
around him.
A crowd of 2,000 anti-Yeltsin campaigners last night cheered a decision of
the Congress, meeting at Moscow's White House, to uphold a vote on Wednesday
by a smaller parliamentary body, the Supreme Soviet, to impeach Mr Yeltsin.
Deputy prime minister Mr Sergei Shakhrai, a close aide to Mr Yeltsin, said
the authorities had no intention of forcibly expelling deputies from the
White House.
But General Pavel Grachev, the defence minister, said police and interior
ministry troops 'were ready to use force against groups of bandits if
provocation threatened peoples' lives' at the gathering.
The government said it was cutting off financing for parliament and taking
over its buildings, its newspaper and its television programmes.
'The whole question is now a war of nerves. The question is who will make
the first mistake,' said Mr Andrei Fyodorov, an aide to Mr Alexander
Rutskoi, the vice-president installed by parliament as temporary president.
Mr Rutskoi, who last night endorsed so far ineffectual calls for a general
strike across Russia in protest at Mr Yeltsin's moves, made clear he would
not stand in the next poll for president.
Mr Yeltsin showed his readiness to put his job on the line along with the
deputies by promising an early presidential poll on June 12, six months
after parliamentary elections and two years ahead of schedule.
He also embarked on a strategy combining intimidation and seduction to
convince deputies and regional councils to give up their resistance to his
moves to break Russia's political deadlock.
A majority of Russia's 88 local councils have joined deputies in denouncing
as unconstitutional the decree dissolving parliament and convening fresh
elections to a modern bicameral assembly. By contrast, only four of the 88
local governments - which, unlike the councils, are mostly appointed by the
president - have come out against Mr Yeltsin.
The government said that only those councils which actually blocked
preparations for elections would be dissolved.
It warned deputies they would be liable to criminal prosecution for
disobeying the president's decree, but said they would be forgiven if they
gave up.
CRISIS IN RUSSIA
Page 2
President vows to fight election next June
Bankers to discuss debt rescheduling
'Dictator' Yeltsin free to mould new order
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
