<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow picks up as Russian
worries abate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices finished higher across the board, with secondary stocks
particularly firm, after worries about political unrest in Russia abated,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 9.78 at 3,547.02. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 advanced 3.25 to 456.20, while the
American SE composite finished 3.20 higher at 450.29 and the Nasdaq
composite 11.98 stronger at 745.54. Trading volume on the New York SE
totalled 289m shares.
Prices rebounded from Tuesday's big losses as soon as the opening bell
sounded. The early gains - the Dow rallied 15 points in the first 30 minutes
 -were partly a natural reaction to the sell-off the day before, and partly
a response to the news of the latest developments from Russia.
The market's biggest fear, that the military would intervene to oppose
President Boris Yeltsin and plunge the country into civil war, was not
realised, and the widespread support for Mr Yeltsin among western nations
reassured investors. The situation in Russia, however, remained uncertain,
and continued to cast a shadow over trading in New York.
Domestic considerations were also influencing market sentiment yesterday.
President Bill Clinton was due to officially present his health care plan to
the nation last night, and the drugs sector remained under pressure ahead of
the speech.
Among the biggest pharmaceutical stocks, Pfizer slipped Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 60 1/2 , Bristol Myers-Squibb Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 58 1/4 and
Johnson &amp; Johnson Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 39 1/4 , but Merck firmed Dollars
 1/8 to Dollars 31 1/2 .
Primerica moved ahead Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 47 1/2 in volume of 2.4m
shares and Travelers edged Dollars  5/8 higher to Dollars 36 5/8 in turnover
of 2.6m on news that Primerica, which already owns 27 per cent of Travelers,
is negotiating a possible stock-swap merger with the insurance group.
Paramount Communications remained very active, advancing Dollars 1 to
Dollars 78 in volume of 4.37m shares as investors and traders continued to
speculate about the takeover battle that has engulfed Paramount between
Viacom, which has made an Dollars 8.2bn bid to buy the entertainment group,
and QVC, which has offered Dollars 9.5bn for Paramount.
QVC, quoted on the Nasdaq market, was in strong demand, climbing Dollars 3
7/8 to Dollars 60 in heavy dealings, while Viacom, traded on the American
Stock Exchange, rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 58 7/8 .
Optimism about the outlook for third-quarter earnings boosted semiconductor
stocks. Texas Instruments jumped Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 77 3/4 , Motorola
added Dollars 2 1/2 at Dollars 94 3/4 , National Semiconductor firmed
Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 20 1/2 and Intel, on the Nasdaq market, strengthened
Dollars 2 to Dollars 67 1/4 .
Canada
TORONTO ended mixed after active turnover. The TSE 300 index gained a net
17.6 at 3,954.9, after trading in negative territory for much of the day,
but falls still led rises at the close by 394 to 321. Volume was 61.2m
shares.
Eleven of the 14 stock groups rose, but gold shares gave back much of
Tuesday's rise, falling 2.22 per cent as the New York spot bullion price
retreated USDollars 8.50 an ounce on indications that the Russian political
crisis had stabilised.
