<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Offshoot sale lifts Tilbury Douglas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TILBURY DOUGLAS, the construction group, lifted interim pre-tax profits from
Pounds 6.98m to Pounds 12.8m, with the help of a Pounds 6.78m profit on the
sale of a subsidiary. The shares were unchanged at 595p.
Mr Michael Bottjer, chief executive, said trading conditions remained
difficult in the first half although there were now signs of a slow recovery
in the UK.
The group is 'avidly' searching for acquisitions, he said, and has net cash
of Pounds 14.4m - up from Pounds 4.83m a year earlier and Pounds 6.94m in
the 1992 balance sheet - following the sale of Douglas Concrete and
Aggregates in May for Pounds 14.7m, which gave a net cash benefit of Pounds
10.8m.
Mr Bottjer said work in hand in the construction division was about the same
as a year ago, although there had been an increase in the proportion coming
from overseas from 3 per cent to 12 per cent.
Margins were better in places such as the Middle and Far East than in the
UK, he said, and the group aims to increase further the proportion of its
overseas work.
In the UK, he saw little sign of recovery in mainstream contracting until
towards the end of 1994. However, some specialist areas, such as heavy
electrical contracting and process engineering were good.
Others, such as interior contracting, largely for the big retail groups, and
piling and foundation work, both of which had suffered in the first half,
were now enjoying a busy period.
The group's Scottish housebuilding business had a good first quarter.
Although business dropped off in the second quarter, it had revived again
since the end of June.
Group turnover was down 11 per cent at Pounds 169.3m, with that from
continuing operations down a similar percentage at Pounds 166.2m.
Pre-interest profits from continuing operations fell 34 per cent to Pounds
3.33m, with Douglas Concrete contributing Pounds 505,000 (Pounds 352,000).
Associates made Pounds 248,000 (Pounds 28,000).
Interest received rose from Pounds 1.56m to Pounds 1.94m. Earnings per
share, boosted by the Douglas Concrete sale, rose from 13.9p to 26.9p. The
interim dividend is maintained at 10.5p.
</TEXT>
