<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Carlton to issue Dollars 200m of perpetual
debt in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARLTON Communications, the UK television company, is to issue Dollars 200m
of perpetual debt in the US, making it the first foreign non-financial
company to tap a market usually the preserve of banks.
Carlton said the deal will hedge its balance sheet by securing long-term
finance for its US investments in a form that is similar to equity but tax
deductible and does not involve diluting share-holders.
The deal, which is being led by Merrill Lynch, involves the issue of
fixed-rate subordinated paper called Exchangeable Capital Securities, which
can be converted at the option of the company into preference shares.
Mr Bernard Cragg, Carlton's finance director, said the issue would be
carried on the company's balance sheet as debt, although it does not have to
be repaid and is free of covenant restrictions.
The deal is expected to offer a yield some 200 basis points above long-dated
Treasury bonds, slightly higher than that on a similar issue by Barclays
Bank.
Merrill Lynch is expected to sell the issue to its retail clients who have
been seeking to improve the return on their investments as yields in the
bond market have fal-len.
Mr Cragg said Carlton, which has no net debt, had been able to exploit the
opportunity because its American Depositary Receipt programme meant it could
meet Securities and Exchange Commission disclosure requirements and had
already received an unpublicised single-A rating from leading rating
agencies.
Carlton could borrow at much cheaper interest rates in the floating rate
eurodollar market, but said a perpetual subordinated issue cost only 60-80
basis points more than a conventional long-term bond.
The company believed the issue was good value at current long-term rates.
'To the extent that people feel that interest rates are going up, we feel
it's a bargain,' Carlton said.
</TEXT>
